    "id": "polymarket_0x638051302276b32a6390605cc91ba3b4403584f9aefd078595498abfa9613cd7",
    "title": "Will the Israeli Knesset be dissolved, triggering new elections, during 2025?",
    "question_type": "binary",
    "options": [
      "Yes",
      "No"
    ],
    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if the 25th Knesset, which is the sitting parliament of Israel, is dissolved between May 12 and December 31, 2025, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No\".\n\nThe primary resolution source for this market is official information from the State of Israel, however a consensus of credible reporting will also be used.\n",
    "outcome": "No",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nThroughout 2025, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu faced repeated threats to his coalition's stability, primarily stemming from the contentious Haredi military draft exemption issue and budget pressures. Despite significant opposition efforts to dissolve the Knesset, most notably a major legislative push in June 2025, the coalition held together. A critical turning point occurred in mid-July when Haredi parties, including Shas and United Torah Judaism (UTJ), quit the government but crucially remained within the ruling coalition, preventing a collapse. By carefully navigating compromises with these factions and maintaining a narrow parliamentary majority, Netanyahu averted early elections, ensuring the Knesset was not dissolved before 2026.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2025-06-11**: Haredi parties threatened to dissolve the Knesset over draft exemptions, prompting intense coalition negotiations and compromises ([art_politics_20250611_006_6adb9a57], [art_politics_20250611_010_2da7c914]).\n- **2025-06-12**: The Israeli opposition's bill to dissolve the Knesset was rejected in a preliminary reading by a vote of 61-53, allowing Netanyahu's government to survive the immediate crisis ([art_politics_20250612_002_8a18ce1a], [art_politics_20250612_004_79b81cf0], [art_politics_20250612_008_0aa75bc0]).\n- **2025-07-15 to 2025-07-17**: The Shas party and United Torah Judaism (UTJ) quit Netanyahu's government over the ongoing draft exemption crisis, placing Netanyahu in a highly vulnerable political position ([art_general_20250715_012_bdbcb21b], [art_general_20250717_009_80ec09ae], [art_general_20250727_005_8faa6308]).\n- **2025-07-21**: Yair Lapid’s Yesh Atid party initiated another process to dissolve the Knesset in response to the perceived coalition weakness ([art_general_20250721_002_647f6fd2]).\n- **2025-07-21**: Despite the Haredi parties leaving the government, they remained in the ruling coalition, keeping the electoral dynamics largely unchanged and preventing the necessary votes for dissolution ([art_general_20250721_005_cf842da0], [art_general_20250717_009_80ec09ae]).\n- **2025-10-19**: Tensions regarding faith, military service, and statehood continued to test the coalition, but no successful dissolution vote materialized ([art_general_20251019_007_4222c778]).\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe survival of the Israeli Knesset throughout 2025 was rooted in the strict parliamentary arithmetic of Netanyahu's right-wing coalition. The root cause of the instability was the deeply divisive issue of Haredi military draft exemptions, which created severe friction between secular and ultra-Orthodox coalition partners. This led to the intermediate mechanism of Haredi parties threatening to topple the government if their demands were not met, culminating in the critical June 2025 dissolution vote. However, Netanyahu's ability to broker a last-minute compromise caused the Haredi parties to back down, resulting in the opposition's bill failing 61-53 ([art_politics_20250612_002_8a18ce1a]). The proximate trigger for the government's continued survival occurred in July when, despite Shas and UTJ resigning from their government ministerial posts in protest, they deliberately chose to remain within the ruling coalition bloc ([art_general_20250717_009_80ec09ae]). Because they provided outside support rather than fully defecting, the opposition lacked the necessary 61 votes to trigger new elections, ultimately resulting in the Knesset remaining intact through the end of the year.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nThe primary countervailing forces were the aggressive efforts by the opposition, led by figures like Yair Lapid, to capitalize on the coalition's internal divisions regarding the Haredi draft. Furthermore, significant public dissatisfaction and international pressure surrounding the ongoing wartime economic reality and geopolitical situation added immense strain on the government. These forces failed to trigger early elections because the ultra-Orthodox parties calculated that their interests (specifically securing draft exemptions and religious funding) were better served by maintaining Netanyahu's right-wing coalition—even from the outside—rather than risking the formation of a secular, center-left government in a new election.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- **E1**: Defeat of the Knesset dissolution bill.\n  - Date: 2025-06-12\n  - Why it matters causally: This was the most direct legislative attempt to trigger early elections. Its failure (61-53) confirmed the coalition's baseline stability.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_politics_20250612_002_8a18ce1a], [art_politics_20250612_004_79b81cf0]\n\n- **E2**: Shas and UTJ parties quit the government but remain in the coalition.\n  - Date: 2025-07-15 to 2025-07-17\n  - Why it matters causally: This action resolved a major internal crisis without collapsing the government. It signaled profound discontent but guaranteed the coalition retained its numerical majority to block dissolution.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_general_20250715_012_bdbcb21b], [art_general_20250717_009_80ec09ae]\n\n- **E3**: Yesh Atid initiates process to dissolve the Knesset.\n  - Date: 2025-07-21\n  - Why it matters causally: Represents the opposition's attempt to strike while the coalition appeared vulnerable post-July crisis. It ultimately failed due to the coalition bloc holding together.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_general_20250721_002_647f6fd2]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Opposition dissolution bill fails 61-53 | [art_politics_20250612_002_8a18ce1a], [art_politics_20250612_004_79b81cf0] | 2025-06-12 | 1.0 | Explicit confirmation of the vote outcome preventing early elections. |\n| Haredi parties back off threat after compromise | [art_politics_20250612_010_2da7c914] | 2025-06-12 | 0.9 | Explains why the June dissolution vote failed. |\n| Shas and UTJ quit government but remain in coalition | [art_general_20250717_009_80ec09ae], [art_general_20250715_012_bdbcb21b] | 2025-07-15 to 2025-07-17 | 1.0 | Explains the major market sentiment shift in mid-July. |\n| Yesh Atid attempts to dissolve Knesset in July | [art_general_20250721_002_647f6fd2] | 2025-07-21 | 0.9 | Demonstrates ongoing pressure that ultimately failed. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\n- **Alternative Path**: Had the Haredi parties (Shas and UTJ) decided to completely withdraw their support and vote with the opposition in July, the government would have lost its majority, leading directly to the dissolution of the Knesset.\n- **Unresolved Uncertainty**: The long-term resolution of the Haredi draft exemption remains unclear; while a temporary compromise held the coalition together in 2025, it remains a structural vulnerability for future governments.\n",
